pr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F35%2F1e%2Fa996736044458587e88d4f8c7fda%2Fap24168811247463.jpg" class="img" alt="Chappell Roan performs during the Bonnaroo Music &amp; Arts Festival on Sunday, June 16, 2024, in Manchester, Tenn. (Photo by Amy Harris/Invision/AP)" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Chappell Roan performs during the Bonnaroo Music &amp; Arts Festival on Sunday, June 16, 2024, in Manchester, Tenn. (Photo by Amy Harris/Invision/AP)                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Amy Harris/Amy Harris/Invision/AP/Invision                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lately, pop music from female artists has provided an outlet for expressing frustration. &lt;/strong&gt;These artists incorporate screaming into their music to convey anger toward various issues such as failed relationships, envious fans and societal norms. They even encourage their concert audiences to join in and release their own frustrations. On &lt;em&gt;Morning Edition&lt;/em&gt;, psychotherapist Jennifer Cox delves into the significance of this trend in the music industry.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-29204" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 819;         --source-height: 461;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspo