ttps://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4872x2741+0+273/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fae%2Fd7%2F5141507249aeba6bdf663d6aef32%2Fgettyimages-2177417560.jpg" class="img" alt="Vice President Harris campaigns in Raleigh, N.C., on Oct. 12 — part of a push to try to shore up her support among Black men." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Vice President Harris campaigns in Raleigh, N.C., on Oct. 12 — part of a push to try to shore up her support among Black men.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Brendan Smialowski/AFP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;With the race so close, NPR's Deepa Shivaram tells&lt;em&gt; Up First&lt;/em&gt; that Harris spending these final weeks trying to appeal to Republican and independent voters.&lt;/strong&gt; She is set to &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1211596885:1260498988"&gt;discuss her new proposals today at a town hall event&lt;/a&gt; with Charlamagne tha God, one of the hosts of &lt;em&gt;The Breakfast Club&lt;/em&gt;. Charlamagne is known for being a challenging interviewer and has been critical of Democratic candidates in the past.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aid workers and human rights groups fear that Israel's new offensive is starving people in north Gaza&lt;/strong&gt;. The plan, which has been in effect for the past two weeks, focuses on the Jabalia refugee camp where Israel claims Hamas was attempting to regroup. The United Nations Relief and Works Agency, which provides aid to Palestinians, reports that civilians in the area are being forced to either leave or face starvation due to blocked food deliveries. Israel has issued an evacuation order for all of north Gaza. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;NPR’s Daniel Estrin spoke with a man named Mohammed El Balaawy, who fled his home in Jabalia.&lt;/strong&gt; El Balaawy stated that he was part of a group of 25 people who escaped while under fire, and 10 of them were injured or killed. His relatives who stayed behind have &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1211596885:1260498988"&gt;run out of food and water&lt;/a&gt;. The practice of "leave or starve" is not an official policy, and the Israeli army denies its implementation.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Biden administration is establishing a new national marine sanctuary off the Central California coast that will protect over 4,500 square miles of ocean. &lt;/strong&gt;The Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary will be the first to be managed by Indigenous people. It &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/10/13/nx-s1-5147914/the-u-s-gets-a-new-national-marine-sanctuary-the-first-led-by-a-tribe"&gt;will be overseen&lt;/a&gt; in collaboration with local tribes and Indigenous groups that will provide guidance to the federal government. This initiative reflects the Biden administration's commitment to involving tribes in decisions regarding the lands and waters that were historically taken from them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-27807" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5896;         --source-height: 3317;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5896x3317+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F94%2F16%2Fa516884c4c218f4d7ce13e0bdb3c%2Fgettyimages-1349072028.jpg" class="img" alt="Photograph of a woman trying on clothes in a store dressing room. She is photographed from behind as she looks at her outfit in the mirror. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 It's important to feel good in your clothes — and sometimes that means reframing your negative self-talk around fashion. &lt;br&gt;                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Igor Alecsander/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sometimes, we tend to criticize our style or body when getting dressed. &lt;/strong&gt;Stylist Sophie Strauss wants to flip the narrative and reframe how we talk about our clothes in relation to our bodies. Here are &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/10/11/g-s1-27723/this-outfit-isnt-flattering-5-common-style-gripes-and-how-to-fix-them"&gt;positive and constructive ways to tackle&lt;/a&gt; style complaints. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;👖 &lt;strong&gt;If you're feeling stuck or bored with your style&lt;/strong&gt;, don't rush to buy new clothes. Take this opportunity to reconsider what you already have and get creative.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;👖 &lt;strong&gt;Saying comments like “this isn’t flattering”&lt;/strong&gt; blames your body. Put the fault back on your clothes by saying, “I don’t like this.”&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;👖 &lt;strong&gt;Remember, anyone can take fashion risks&lt;/strong&gt;; it just takes confidence, which can be built.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;👖&lt;strong&gt;One misconception about personal style is that it’s a race&lt;/strong&gt; to be the most unique person. It should be all about making the right decisions for you.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check out &lt;/strong&gt;the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/10/11/g-s1-27723/this-outfit-isnt-flattering-5-common-style-gripes-and-how-to-fix-them"&gt;full list of how to fix common style gripes&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Picture show&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-15018" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 6000;         --source-height: 3375;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+313/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4c%2Fb0%2F97ffcc0146c4bf0829820b007f19%2Fcolombia-manacillos-1.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+313/resize/600/quality/85/format/w